[2024-01-07 10:52:25] 我: The point is to nail down some good values and metrics, and pleasure and success will naturally emerge as a result. These things are side effects of good values. By themselves, they are empty highs.
[2024-01-07 11:05:33] 我: When we have poor values—that is, poor standards we set for ourselves and others—we are essentially
[2024-01-07 11:05:42] 我: giving fucks about the things that don’t matter, things that in fact make our life worse. But when we choose better values, we are able to divert our fucks to something better—toward things that matter, things that improve the state of our well-being and that generate happiness, pleasure, and success as side effects.

[2024-01-07 21:54:42] 我: We shouldn’t seek to find the ultimate “right” answer for ourselves, but rather, we should seek to chip away at the ways that we’re wrong today so that we can be a little less wrong tomorrow.
[2024-01-07 22:00:08] 我: Many people become so obsessed with being “right” about their life that they never end up actually living it.

[2024-01-07 22:04:45] 我: Being wrong opens us up to the possibility of change. Being wrong brings the opportunity for growth. It means not cutting your arm open to cure a cold or splashing dog piss on your face to look young again. It means not thinking “mediocre” is a vegetable, and not being afraid to care about things.
[2024-01-07 22:07:31] 我: Because here’s something that’s weird but
[2024-01-07 22:07:40] 我: true: we don’t actually know what a positive or negative experience is. Some of the most difficult and stressful moments of our lives also end up being the most formative and motivating. Some of the best and most gratifying experiences of our lives are also the most distracting and demotivating. Don’t trust your conception of positive/negative experiences
[2024-01-07 22:08:38] 我: All that we know for certain is what hurts in the moment and what doesn’t. And
[2024-01-07 22:08:47] 我: that’s not worth much
[2024-01-07 22:26:41] 我: How so? Well, our brain is always trying to make sense of our current situation
[2024-01-07 22:26:51] 我: based on what we already believe and have already experienced. Every new piece of information is measured against the values and conclusions we already have
[2024-01-07 22:27:15] 我: As a result, our brain is always biased toward what we feel to be true in that moment. So when we have a great relationship with our sister, we’ll interpret most of our memories about her in a positive light. But when the relationship sours, we’ll often come to see those exact same memories
[2024-01-07 22:27:25] 我: differently, reinventing them in such a way as to explain our present-day anger toward her
[2024-01-07 22:29:13] 我: That sweet gift she gave us last Christmas is now remembered as patronizing and condescending. That time she forgot to invite us to her lake house is now seen not as an innocent mistake but as horrible negligence.

